WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.640
My journey to this conference started one year and one day ago.

00:00:15.640 --> 00:00:22.799
As with many of you, it started with a tweet from Hadley Wickham.

00:00:22.799 --> 00:00:25.600
How much more could you want than this?

00:00:25.600 --> 00:00:28.840
RStudio is hiring a director of education.

00:00:28.840 --> 00:00:33.599
Please apply if you love stats and education.

00:00:33.599 --> 00:00:40.040
At this time, I was teaching big data for a consulting company that had been acquired

00:00:40.040 --> 00:00:44.040
by a very large technology company.

00:00:44.040 --> 00:00:48.520
I was putting on about 100,000 air miles per year.

00:00:48.520 --> 00:00:53.680
At that level, you get to know the TSA folks on a first-name basis.

00:00:54.279 --> 00:00:59.680
Hey Tom, how's the wife and kids?

00:00:59.680 --> 00:01:03.959
And it seemed like staying around home might be a little bit more fun.

00:01:03.959 --> 00:01:08.000
So I interviewed with, basically, my heroes.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.680
Garrett Grollemund, Menechet and Gaya Rundle, Hadley Wickham.

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:19.720
Finally, it comes to the point where I interview with Tarif, who's the president of RStudio.

00:01:19.720 --> 00:01:22.839
And I'm a little nervous.

00:01:22.839 --> 00:01:26.800
And I get a little bit more nervous when he tells me, you know, I'm not sure you're who

00:01:26.800 --> 00:01:30.360
we're looking for.

00:01:30.360 --> 00:01:34.480
I don't think you're going to work out because we're thinking a little bit bigger than you

00:01:34.480 --> 00:01:35.480
are.

00:01:35.480 --> 00:01:40.440
We're thinking that we really want to equip everyone, regardless of means, to participate

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:45.360
in a global economy that rewards data literacy.

00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:47.559
Whoa.

00:01:47.559 --> 00:01:50.360
So I had to go home and think about that.

00:01:50.360 --> 00:01:53.120
And we had coffee scheduled for the next day.

00:01:53.120 --> 00:01:59.599
And I came in and I met with him again, and I gave him my best shot.

00:01:59.599 --> 00:02:04.440
And as a result, I am now the director of education at RStudio.

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:06.639
And the shot I gave him was this.

00:02:06.639 --> 00:02:12.000
This is what's called a BHAG, a Big Hairy Audacious Goal.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:14.440
Comes from an old book called Built to Last.

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:17.479
And my BHAG was really simple.

00:02:17.479 --> 00:02:23.320
RStudio education's mission is going to be to train the next million R users.

00:02:23.320 --> 00:02:27.600
Now this sounds sort of preposterous when you first think about it.

00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:31.240
But frankly, it's smaller than the population of San Jose.

00:02:31.240 --> 00:02:32.600
Not so bad.

00:02:32.600 --> 00:02:38.520
And it is a little bit larger than the number of people who own Klingon dictionaries.

00:02:38.520 --> 00:02:43.619
By the way, there are 300,000 people that own Klingon dictionaries.

00:02:43.619 --> 00:02:49.500
This particular one says, I must attend RStudio Conf.

00:02:49.500 --> 00:02:53.179
So it's easy to make a Big Hairy Audacious Goal.

00:02:53.179 --> 00:02:56.020
But how do you execute on it, right?

00:02:56.020 --> 00:02:58.059
So I'm a member of AA.

00:02:58.059 --> 00:03:00.380
No, I'm not an alcoholic.

00:03:00.380 --> 00:03:03.660
I'm actually an analyst's anonymous.

00:03:03.660 --> 00:03:06.940
I was an industry analyst for 15 years.

00:03:06.940 --> 00:03:12.100
And when you ask an analyst, tell me how you're going to do something, they start asking questions

00:03:12.100 --> 00:03:13.100
back.

00:03:13.580 --> 00:03:16.220
And my questions were, well, who learns R?

00:03:16.220 --> 00:03:17.899
And why do they learn R?

00:03:17.899 --> 00:03:19.380
And how do they learn R?

00:03:19.380 --> 00:03:21.860
And what keeps them from learning R?

00:03:21.860 --> 00:03:24.779
Well, again, analysts are trained to do this.

00:03:24.779 --> 00:03:29.899
I said, well, the clear way we answer these questions is we do a survey.

00:03:29.899 --> 00:03:33.660
And I brought this up to Hadley as a proposal for doing this talk.

00:03:33.660 --> 00:03:39.020
And Hadley comes back and says, gee, using data to make decisions.

00:03:39.020 --> 00:03:42.419
I think I've heard of that somewhere before.

00:03:42.419 --> 00:03:46.779
So on December 6th, I put out this tweet of my own, which is, do you wonder how and

00:03:46.779 --> 00:03:48.660
why people learn R?

00:03:48.660 --> 00:03:52.500
And if you've learned or are planning to learn R, fill out our five-minute survey.

00:03:52.500 --> 00:03:59.740
Now, thanks to Laura Acion, who's in Argentina, we also got a Spanish language translation

00:03:59.740 --> 00:04:00.899
of the entire survey.

00:04:00.899 --> 00:04:03.460
This went up a few days later.

00:04:03.460 --> 00:04:06.779
And as a result, we actually gathered data.

00:04:06.779 --> 00:04:13.059
So today, I'm here to announce RStudio's Learning R survey is now published.

00:04:13.059 --> 00:04:16.899
It was fielded between December 6th and December 31st.

00:04:16.899 --> 00:04:24.179
The respondents were solicited from community.rstudio.com, Twitter followers of RStudio employees and

00:04:24.179 --> 00:04:28.380
colleagues, and reddit.com data science.

00:04:28.380 --> 00:04:32.140
What I think is really terrific is we received 3,300 responses.

00:04:32.140 --> 00:04:41.059
I would have been happy with about 1,000, but 3,300, about 10% are Spanish speaking.

00:04:41.059 --> 00:04:44.940
And all of this data is now at this repo.

00:04:44.940 --> 00:04:49.899
Every single bit of data we collected and all the plots I'm about to show you are available

00:04:49.899 --> 00:04:54.220
for you to peruse and the code necessary to analyze it.

00:04:54.220 --> 00:04:58.820
It's about 2,000 lines of our markdown.

00:04:58.820 --> 00:05:02.019
Now here's where we have to do the warning messages.

00:05:02.019 --> 00:05:06.380
First warning, significant sampling bias may be present.

00:05:06.380 --> 00:05:10.579
These results are not necessarily representative of the general R population.

00:05:10.579 --> 00:05:15.540
This is, in fact, 3,300 of RStudio's closest friends.

00:05:15.540 --> 00:05:19.059
The other thing is there's a lot of open text in this survey.

00:05:19.059 --> 00:05:25.019
And that means if you're in K through 12 and you want to teach your kids data science using

00:05:25.019 --> 00:05:29.140
this survey, you should know that this is restricted data.

00:05:29.260 --> 00:05:33.220
K through 17 requires accompanying parent or guardian.

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:36.059
So just be very aware of that.

00:05:36.059 --> 00:05:38.299
Now we're going to blast through the data.

00:05:38.299 --> 00:05:44.200
There's no way I can do in 20 minutes any real honor to this data.

00:05:44.200 --> 00:05:47.019
But let me just give you the highlights.

00:05:47.019 --> 00:05:48.019
Who learns R?

00:05:48.019 --> 00:05:52.500
Well, here's a choropleth of the respondents to our survey.

00:05:52.500 --> 00:05:57.299
We got responses from 110 different countries.

00:05:57.299 --> 00:05:58.540
These are the top 10.

00:05:58.940 --> 00:06:02.339
Again, thanks to Laura, we have Argentina as number three.

00:06:02.339 --> 00:06:05.739
She tweeted through R ladies there.

00:06:05.739 --> 00:06:08.859
Most respondents consider themselves to be intermediate users.

00:06:08.859 --> 00:06:09.859
They're not experts.

00:06:09.859 --> 00:06:11.380
They're not beginners.

00:06:11.380 --> 00:06:12.739
And 3% say none.

00:06:12.739 --> 00:06:19.179
And those are really important people because those are the people we're trying to reach.

00:06:19.179 --> 00:06:21.739
Males made up about 75% of respondents.

00:06:21.739 --> 00:06:24.980
I had thought we were doing better on diversity than we are.

00:06:24.980 --> 00:06:27.700
This is an area where we have some work to do.

00:06:27.700 --> 00:06:31.540
The mean age was 35, although there's clearly a long tail.

00:06:31.540 --> 00:06:32.540
You can see where I am.

00:06:32.540 --> 00:06:36.140
I'm kind of over towards the right-hand side there.

00:06:36.140 --> 00:06:40.299
And respondents started learning R at a mean age of 30.

00:06:40.299 --> 00:06:46.260
So basically most people in our survey had an average level of experience with R of about

00:06:46.260 --> 00:06:51.140
five years, although clearly there's big tails on both ends.

00:06:51.140 --> 00:06:55.420
Our community mostly has advanced degrees.

00:06:55.420 --> 00:06:58.500
Master's is number one, doctorate number two, bachelor number three.

00:06:58.500 --> 00:07:01.459
So these are pretty educated people.

00:07:01.459 --> 00:07:05.179
And almost half of them work in research or education.

00:07:05.179 --> 00:07:10.700
So a very educated group, but also working in the research or education community.

00:07:10.700 --> 00:07:14.179
Technology is number three, and health and medicine is number four.

00:07:14.179 --> 00:07:16.260
So that's who answered our survey.

00:07:16.260 --> 00:07:20.619
Let's go on to why do they learn R. Well, okay.

00:07:20.619 --> 00:07:25.619
This is where we start getting into data that's going to make you go, duh.

00:07:25.619 --> 00:07:29.339
Most of them learn it to do statistical analysis.

00:07:29.339 --> 00:07:35.260
But what's interesting is about one in six did this because they were personally interested.

00:07:35.260 --> 00:07:36.739
They're interested in learning stats.

00:07:36.739 --> 00:07:37.899
So that's kind of cool.

00:07:37.899 --> 00:07:42.320
And about 13% said they think it'll open new career opportunities.

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:44.160
So that's really neat.

00:07:44.160 --> 00:07:47.619
So then we asked them, okay, what tools do you use with R?

00:07:47.619 --> 00:07:52.859
And here we get some, or what applications do you use, I'm sorry.

00:07:52.859 --> 00:07:57.260
And here, statistical analysis, number one, again, duh.

00:07:57.260 --> 00:07:58.260
Visualization number two.

00:07:58.260 --> 00:08:01.299
And in fact, there's some detail here that's interesting.

00:08:01.299 --> 00:08:05.820
In the English language version, visualization is number one.

00:08:05.820 --> 00:08:08.179
Spanish language statistics is number one.

00:08:08.179 --> 00:08:11.619
So a little bit of difference between the two populations.

00:08:11.619 --> 00:08:13.339
So how do they learn R?

00:08:13.339 --> 00:08:16.380
This is education, so we want to know how they're learning.

00:08:16.940 --> 00:08:20.899
And respondents mostly learn R on their own.

00:08:20.899 --> 00:08:25.140
To me, this is obvious, but at the same time, I think one of the biggest takeaways from

00:08:25.140 --> 00:08:26.820
this survey.

00:08:26.820 --> 00:08:30.779
People are learning R on their own.

00:08:30.779 --> 00:08:32.900
It's a problem, actually, as we'll see.

00:08:32.900 --> 00:08:37.099
I had thought online courses would be higher, but it's not.

00:08:37.099 --> 00:08:40.700
People are using books and online materials, Stack Overflow.

00:08:40.700 --> 00:08:43.700
You can actually learn R from Stack Overflow.

00:08:43.700 --> 00:08:45.260
We don't recommend it.

00:08:45.260 --> 00:08:53.739
If you heard Fiene's talk this morning, exploration is not the most efficient way to get there,

00:08:53.739 --> 00:08:56.979
but it's certainly one of the ways you can learn.

00:08:56.979 --> 00:09:02.979
If we think about some of our own packages, like the Tidyverse, has that had any effect?

00:09:02.979 --> 00:09:12.020
Only 45% learned using the Tidyverse, but today, do you use the Tidyverse when you use

00:09:12.020 --> 00:09:13.020
R today?

00:09:13.179 --> 00:09:16.780
67%, two-thirds of people are using the Tidyverse.

00:09:16.780 --> 00:09:20.460
So I think Tidyverse has really moved the needle.

00:09:20.460 --> 00:09:24.580
Now one question I'd like to ask, this is a very specific question.

00:09:24.580 --> 00:09:28.460
It's used for computing something called the net promoter score.

00:09:28.460 --> 00:09:33.859
People are really excited about R. They love R. As a matter of fact, when we ask this question,

00:09:33.859 --> 00:09:40.700
how likely are you to recommend R to a colleague, friend, or a family member, we get a net promoter

00:09:40.700 --> 00:09:45.140
score of 71%.

00:09:45.140 --> 00:09:46.859
And that is actually excellent.

00:09:46.859 --> 00:09:50.900
If it were four points higher, it would be world class.

00:09:50.900 --> 00:09:54.219
That type of loyalty cannot be bought.

00:09:54.219 --> 00:09:55.859
It's a fabulous number.

00:09:55.859 --> 00:10:01.340
It's in the level of brands like Apple and Google and things of that sort.

00:10:01.340 --> 00:10:07.239
The tools that people use, the IDE gets love from our friends, no surprise there.

00:10:07.239 --> 00:10:11.039
But look, Microsoft Excel, still showing up there.

00:10:11.039 --> 00:10:12.760
We have to reach Excel users.

00:10:12.760 --> 00:10:17.440
All right, the last bit of data, what keeps them from learning R?

00:10:17.440 --> 00:10:19.640
So we'll start with the R users themselves.

00:10:19.640 --> 00:10:22.080
What did they find most difficult?

00:10:22.080 --> 00:10:25.239
And number one is error messages.

00:10:25.239 --> 00:10:28.000
I don't think that's any surprise to any of us.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.479
But let's look at the non-R users.

00:10:30.479 --> 00:10:32.799
So it's a pretty small sample here.

00:10:32.799 --> 00:10:35.840
So beware, these numbers are a little squishy.

00:10:35.840 --> 00:10:39.599
But nonetheless, language syntax is number one.

00:10:39.599 --> 00:10:42.320
Getting started is number two.

00:10:42.320 --> 00:10:49.200
So quick recap, the majority of R users are pretty sophisticated and educated researchers.

00:10:49.200 --> 00:10:53.400
They learn R by themselves and not necessarily through formal courses.

00:10:53.400 --> 00:10:57.400
And one of their biggest challenges for learners is getting started.

00:10:57.400 --> 00:10:59.640
OK, so what?

00:10:59.640 --> 00:11:01.520
What can we do?

00:11:01.520 --> 00:11:07.000
So here's where I want to just give you a few activities we're doing within RStudio

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:09.320
and within our education department.

00:11:09.320 --> 00:11:14.400
The first thing we can do is hire more teachers that can teach R. I have the privilege of

00:11:14.400 --> 00:11:20.080
working with what I believe are some of the best teachers in the world for teaching this.

00:11:20.080 --> 00:11:23.719
You've met most of them at this conference.

00:11:23.719 --> 00:11:26.880
Some of them have spoken either yesterday or today.

00:11:26.880 --> 00:11:30.799
But I wanted to alert people to the fact that we've hired a couple more.

00:11:30.799 --> 00:11:33.880
Greg Wilson, I'll talk about him in a moment.

00:11:33.880 --> 00:11:37.919
Allison Hill is actually here today handling this session.

00:11:37.919 --> 00:11:42.559
And if you were in the advanced R markdown session, you would have seen her teach for

00:11:42.559 --> 00:11:44.840
the entire first day of that.

00:11:44.840 --> 00:11:45.840
Fabulous people.

00:11:45.840 --> 00:11:49.799
You're going to see them on the same page as all the other teachers soon because they

00:11:49.799 --> 00:11:51.760
are real stars.

00:11:51.760 --> 00:11:56.479
But we're announcing a program today called RStudio Certified Teachers.

00:11:56.479 --> 00:12:00.280
These are new programs beginning this month.

00:12:00.760 --> 00:12:04.239
It's a two-level program with both instructors and coaches.

00:12:04.239 --> 00:12:09.359
So the idea is we can certify instructors, but we can also certify other people to certify

00:12:09.359 --> 00:12:11.359
instructors.

00:12:11.359 --> 00:12:16.559
This is headed up by Greg Wilson, who is the cofounder of Software Carpentry.

00:12:16.559 --> 00:12:20.200
Also a former professor at the University of Toronto.

00:12:20.200 --> 00:12:24.320
This certifies teaching skills and knowledge of RStudio tools.

00:12:24.320 --> 00:12:28.599
We think this is going to be great for driving a whole new cadre of teachers.

00:12:28.599 --> 00:12:30.520
So that's step one, more teachers.

00:12:30.520 --> 00:12:32.919
But remember, most people are self-taught.

00:12:32.919 --> 00:12:35.840
So we need more tools as well.

00:12:35.840 --> 00:12:41.320
So here's one that most people should know, but they probably don't.

00:12:41.320 --> 00:12:47.880
That we provide free academic licensing for all of our RStudio professional software.

00:12:47.880 --> 00:12:49.039
It's free.

00:12:49.039 --> 00:12:59.039
All you have to do is give us a course syllabus and any certified academic institution.

00:12:59.039 --> 00:13:04.500
I don't care whether you're K through 12, community college, university, doesn't matter.

00:13:04.500 --> 00:13:06.400
You get our tools for free.

00:13:06.400 --> 00:13:10.539
If you're doing research rather than teaching, you get a 50% discount.

00:13:10.539 --> 00:13:15.080
We want you to use our professional tools, and all the details are on our website under

00:13:15.080 --> 00:13:16.500
the pricing page.

00:13:16.500 --> 00:13:18.640
So that's tool number one.

00:13:18.640 --> 00:13:21.520
Tool number two is data science in a box.

00:13:21.520 --> 00:13:27.219
This is an initiative that Minay Chetinkaya-Rundle started based upon her experience at Duke.

00:13:27.219 --> 00:13:33.479
It's an entire introductory statistics course with all the slides, all the exercises, all

00:13:33.479 --> 00:13:35.320
the exams, all the answers.

00:13:35.320 --> 00:13:40.260
Well, don't show your students the answers, but nonetheless, it has everything you need

00:13:40.260 --> 00:13:42.039
to really teach a course.

00:13:42.039 --> 00:13:44.320
This is open source.

00:13:44.320 --> 00:13:49.539
Go to datasciencebox.org, and you can get all the materials and start teaching with

00:13:49.539 --> 00:13:50.539
them.

00:13:50.539 --> 00:13:52.020
So that's number two.

00:13:52.020 --> 00:13:54.280
Number three is online books.

00:13:54.280 --> 00:13:56.020
We don't often think about this.

00:13:56.020 --> 00:14:00.739
Many of the people at RStudio are authors, and they've negotiated with their publishers

00:14:00.739 --> 00:14:05.099
so they can actually publish their books online for free.

00:14:05.099 --> 00:14:09.619
So R for Data Science, if you didn't know this, this is available online for free.

00:14:09.619 --> 00:14:12.340
You can go in and read the latest version.

00:14:12.359 --> 00:14:15.119
Advanced R is also online.

00:14:15.119 --> 00:14:19.840
Blog Down, Creating Websites with R Markdown, Hands-on Programming with R. I've thrown in

00:14:19.840 --> 00:14:25.080
another one, Geocomputation in R, simply because it's a book I've been learning from lately.

00:14:25.080 --> 00:14:30.880
And what I love about it is it targets an audience that is not a data scientist.

00:14:30.880 --> 00:14:34.280
Somebody wants to create maps, do geographical information systems.

00:14:34.280 --> 00:14:40.640
So I love this book because it's an entirely different area of investigation.

00:14:40.640 --> 00:14:44.099
The next tool I'm going to talk about is one I'm not going to talk about.

00:14:44.099 --> 00:14:48.500
You're going to hear from RStudio Cloud from Mel Gregory, but it's probably one of the

00:14:48.500 --> 00:14:50.900
most important introductions we've done.

00:14:50.900 --> 00:14:55.419
This is going to allow you to do anything that we do on the professional tools in the

00:14:55.419 --> 00:14:56.419
cloud.

00:14:56.419 --> 00:14:57.419
That's Mel.

00:14:57.419 --> 00:14:59.700
She's coming up at 2.09 today.

00:14:59.700 --> 00:15:03.340
Right here in this room, don't go anywhere.

00:15:03.340 --> 00:15:06.059
But as part of that, we do have primers.

00:15:06.059 --> 00:15:09.260
These are tutorials for people who want to learn on their own.

00:15:09.260 --> 00:15:15.960
You can create an account at RStudio Cloud and just go in and learn R, and it's free.

00:15:15.960 --> 00:15:21.760
So this is another way that we're allowing people to self-teach to really learn how to

00:15:21.760 --> 00:15:23.880
use R on their own.

00:15:23.880 --> 00:15:28.239
But there's one more thing, and I just want to leave you with this one.

00:15:28.239 --> 00:15:30.440
One more piece of data that I think is really key.

00:15:30.440 --> 00:15:35.960
We've heard it a little bit in the prior talks here, but we have data to support this.

00:15:35.960 --> 00:15:41.859
So if we ask people what they love most about using R, and we actually asked it in kind

00:15:41.859 --> 00:15:46.239
of that way, what did we discover?

00:15:46.239 --> 00:15:48.000
Community is number one.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:51.460
The community is really what makes this work.

00:15:51.460 --> 00:15:55.099
Now here's the sad part, also in the data.

00:15:55.099 --> 00:16:02.500
15% of our users have no one else in their work group that knows R. They're completely

00:16:02.500 --> 00:16:04.479
on their own.

00:16:04.479 --> 00:16:11.080
If we add in one person, it's zero or one, it's one in four, 25%, have no one to work

00:16:11.080 --> 00:16:15.840
with when they're doing R. And as all of you know, it's one of the exciting things about

00:16:15.840 --> 00:16:20.080
using R. It's being able to share your results, publish them.

00:16:20.080 --> 00:16:24.960
So I challenge each of you to go off and teach R to a colleague.

00:16:24.960 --> 00:16:27.440
This is why I felt pretty good about my BHAG.

00:16:27.440 --> 00:16:32.039
I'm pretty sure we can teach a million R users.

00:16:32.039 --> 00:16:36.640
If every one of you goes off and grabs a colleague and says, let me tell you how you

00:16:36.640 --> 00:16:43.000
can do that thing you're doing in Excel and do it repeatably and reliably.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:45.400
I say those words specifically.

00:16:45.400 --> 00:16:48.719
Remember back to Tareef's talk yesterday.

00:16:48.719 --> 00:16:50.799
Seems like forever ago, doesn't it?

00:16:50.799 --> 00:16:53.979
But Tareef's talk when we opened the conference.

00:16:53.979 --> 00:16:58.280
The printing press was a new way of communicating with the rest of the world.

00:16:58.280 --> 00:17:01.479
It was a way to share knowledge.

00:17:01.479 --> 00:17:08.859
These tools are, the tools we sell, are things that allow us to create our own knowledge.

00:17:08.859 --> 00:17:10.599
We start from data.

00:17:10.599 --> 00:17:15.040
We create open processes that can be verified by other people.

00:17:15.040 --> 00:17:22.439
And then we create provably, if not correct, at least close to correct results.

00:17:22.439 --> 00:17:25.359
We are the people that are creating knowledge.

00:17:25.359 --> 00:17:30.959
And that's why we believe that by training the next million R users, we can equip everyone

00:17:30.959 --> 00:17:37.520
regardless of means to participate in a global economy that rewards data literacy.

00:17:37.520 --> 00:17:41.160
And each one of you is going to be a part of that.

00:17:41.160 --> 00:17:43.160
Thank you very much.

00:17:43.160 --> 00:17:57.160
Okay, we have time for a few questions.

00:17:57.160 --> 00:17:58.160
No questions.

